# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: galois-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] In mathematics, the **Abel–Ruffini theorem** (also known as **Abel's impossibility theorem**) states that there is no solution in radicals to general polynomial equations of degree five or higher with arbitrary coefficients.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Here, *general* means that the coefficients of the equation are viewed and manipulated as indeterminates.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] The theorem is named after Paolo Ruffini, who made an incomplete proof in 1799 (which was refined and completed in 1813 and accepted by Cauchy) and Niels Henrik Abel, who provided a proof in 1824.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] The term can also refer to the slightly stronger result that there are equations of degree five and higher that cannot be solved by radicals.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] This does not follow from Abel's statement of the theorem, but is a corollary of his proof, as his proof is based on the fact that some polynomials in the coefficients of the equation are not the zero polynomial.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] This improved statement follows directly from Galois theory § A non-solvable quintic example.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] is the simplest equation that cannot be solved in radicals, and that *almost all* polynomials of degree five or higher cannot be solved in radicals.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] The impossibility of solving in degree five or higher contrasts with the case of lower degree: one has the quadratic formula, the cubic formula, and the quartic formula for degrees two, three, and four, respectively.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Polynomial equations of degree two can be solved with the quadratic formula, which has been known since antiquity.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Similarly the cubic formula for degree three, and the quartic formula for degree four, were found during the 16th century.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] At that time a fundamental problem was whether equations of higher degree could be solved in a similar way.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] The fact that every polynomial equation of positive degree has solutions, possibly non-real, was asserted during the 17th century, but completely proved only at the beginning of the 19th century.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] This is the fundamental theorem of algebra, which does not provide any tool for computing the solutions, although several methods are known for approximating all solutions to any desired accuracy.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] From the 16th century to the beginning of the 19th century, the main problem of algebra was to search for a formula for the solutions of polynomial equations of degree five and higher, hence the name the "fundamental theorem of algebra".
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] This meant a solution in radicals, that is, an expression involving only the coefficients of the equation, and the operations of addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, and nth root extraction.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] The Abel–Ruffini theorem proves that this is impossible.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] However, this impossibility does not imply that a specific equation of any degree cannot be solved in radicals.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] On the contrary, there are equations of any degree that can be solved in radicals.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] This is the case of the equation $x^{n}-1=0$ for any n, and the equations defined by cyclotomic polynomials, all of whose solutions can be expressed in radicals.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Abel's proof of the theorem does not explicitly contain the assertion that there are specific equations that cannot be solved by radicals.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Soon after Abel's publication of his proof, Évariste Galois introduced a theory, now called Galois theory, that allows deciding, for any given equation, whether it is solvable in radicals.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] This was purely theoretical before the rise of electronic computers.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] With modern computers and programs, deciding whether a polynomial is solvable by radicals can be done for polynomials of degree greater than 100.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Computing the solutions in radicals of solvable polynomials requires huge computations.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Even for the degree five, the expression of the solutions is so huge that it has no practical interest.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] The proof of the Abel–Ruffini theorem predates Galois theory.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] However, Galois theory allows a better understanding of the subject, and modern proofs are generally based on it, while the original proofs of the Abel–Ruffini theorem are still presented for historical purposes.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] An algebraic solution of a polynomial equation is an expression involving the four basic arithmetic operations (addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division), and root extractions.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Such an expression may be viewed as the description of a computation that starts from the coefficients of the equation to be solved and proceeds by computing some numbers, one after the other.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] At each step of the computation, one may consider the smallest field that contains all numbers that have been computed so far.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] This field is changed only for the steps involving the computation of an nth root.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] For having normal extensions, which are fundamental for the theory, one must refine the sequence of fields as follows.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] So, if one starts from a solution in terms of radicals, one gets an increasing sequence of fields such that the last one contains the solution, and each is a normal extension of the preceding one with a Galois group that is cyclic.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Conversely, if one has such a sequence of fields, the equation is solvable in terms of radicals.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] For proving this, it suffices to prove that a normal extension with a cyclic Galois group can be built from a succession of radical extensions.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] The Galois correspondence establishes a one to one correspondence between the subextensions of a normal field extension $F/E$ and the subgroups of the Galois group of the extension.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] This correspondence maps a field K such $E\subseteq K\subseteq F$ to the Galois group $\operatorname {Gal} (F/K)$ of the automorphisms of F that leave K fixed, and, conversely, maps a subgroup H of $\operatorname {Gal} (F/E)$ to the field of the elements of F that are fixed by H.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] (Solvable groups are commonly defined with abelian instead of cyclic quotient groups, but the fundamental theorem of finite abelian groups shows that the two definitions are equivalent).
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] So, for proving the Abel–Ruffini theorem, it remains to show that the symmetric group $S_{5}$ is not solvable, and that there are polynomials with symmetric Galois groups.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] For *n* ≥ 5, the symmetric group ${\mathcal {S}}_{n}$ of degree n has only the alternating group ${\mathcal {A}}_{n}$ as a nontrivial normal subgroup (see Symmetric group § Normal subgroups).
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] For *n* ≥ 5, the alternating group ${\mathcal {A}}_{n}$ is simple (that is, it does not have any nontrivial normal subgroup) and not abelian.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] This implies that both ${\mathcal {A}}_{n}$ and ${\mathcal {S}}_{n}$ are not solvable for *n* ≥ 5.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Thus, the Abel–Ruffini theorem results from the existence of polynomials with a symmetric Galois group; this will be shown in the next section.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] On the other hand, for *n* ≤ 4, the symmetric group and all its subgroups are solvable.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] This explains the existence of the quadratic, cubic, and quartic formulas, since a major result of Galois theory is that a polynomial equation has a solution in radicals if and only if its Galois group is solvable (the term "solvable group" takes its origin from this theorem).
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] where $a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n}$ are distinct indeterminates.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] This is an equation defined over the field $F=\mathbb {Q} (a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n})$ of the rational fractions in $a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n}$ with rational number coefficients.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] The original Abel–Ruffini theorem asserts that, for *n* ≥ 5, this equation is not solvable in radicals.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] For proving that the Galois group is ${\mathcal {S}}_{n},$ it is simpler to start from the roots.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Let $H=\mathbb {Q} (x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n})$ be the field of the rational fractions in $x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n},$ and $K=\mathbb {Q} (b_{1},\ldots ,b_{n})$ be its subfield generated by the coefficients of $P(x).$ The permutations of the $x_{i}$ induce automorphisms of H.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Vieta's formulas imply that every element of K is a symmetric function of the $x_{i},$ and is thus fixed by all these automorphisms.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] The fundamental theorem of symmetric polynomials implies that the $b_{i}$ are algebraic independent, and thus that the map that sends each $a_{i}$ to the corresponding $b_{i}$ is a field isomorphism from F to K.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] This means that one may consider $P(x)=0$ as a generic equation.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] This finishes the proof that the Galois group of a general equation is the symmetric group, and thus proves the original Abel–Ruffini theorem, which asserts that the general polynomial equation of degree n cannot be solved in radicals for *n* ≥ 5.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] The equation $x^{5}-x-1=0$ is not solvable in radicals, as will be explained below.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Let G be its Galois group, which acts faithfully on the set of complex roots of q.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Numbering the roots lets one identify G with a subgroup of the symmetric group ${\mathcal {S}}_{5}$ .
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Since $q{\bmod {3}}$ is irreducible in $\mathbb {F} _{3}[x]$ , the same principle shows that G contains a 5-cycle.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Because 5 is prime, any transposition and 5-cycle in ${\mathcal {S}}_{5}$ generate the whole group; see Symmetric group § Generators and relations.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Since the group ${\mathcal {S}}_{5}$ is not solvable, the equation $x^{5}-x-1=0$ is not solvable in radicals.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Testing whether a specific quintic is solvable in radicals can be done by using Cayley's resolvent.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] This is a univariate polynomial of degree six whose coefficients are polynomials in the coefficients of a generic quintic.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] A specific irreducible quintic is solvable in radicals if and only, when its coefficients are substituted in Cayley's resolvent, the resulting sextic polynomial has a rational root, which can be easily tested for using the rational root theorem.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Around 1770, Joseph Louis Lagrange began the groundwork that unified the many different methods that had been used up to that point to solve equations, relating them to the theory of groups of permutations, in the form of Lagrange resolvents.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] This innovative work by Lagrange was a precursor to Galois theory, and its failure to develop solutions for equations of fifth and higher degrees hinted that such solutions might be impossible, but it did not provide conclusive proof.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] I shall set forth my investigations of this at greater length in another place." Actually, Gauss published nothing else on this subject.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] The theorem was first nearly proved by Paolo Ruffini in 1799.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Abel wrote: "The first and, if I am not mistaken, the only one who, before me, has sought to prove the impossibility of the algebraic solution of general equations is the mathematician Ruffini.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] But his memoir is so complicated that it is very difficult to determine the validity of his argument.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] The proof also, as it was discovered later, was incomplete.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Ruffini assumed that all radicals that he was dealing with could be expressed from the roots of the polynomial using field operations alone; in modern terms, he assumed that the radicals belonged to the splitting field of the polynomial.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] To see why this is really an extra assumption, consider, for instance, the polynomial $P(x)=x^{3}-15x-20$ .
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] According to Cardano's formula, one of its roots (all of them, actually) can be expressed as the sum of a cube root of $10+5i$ with a cube root of $10-5i$ .
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] While Cauchy either did not notice Ruffini's assumption or felt that it was a minor one, most historians believe that the proof was not complete until Abel proved the theorem on natural irrationalities, which asserts that the assumption holds in the case of general polynomials.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] The Abel–Ruffini theorem is thus generally credited to Abel, who published a proof compressed into just six pages in 1824.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] (Abel adopted a very terse style to save paper and money: the proof was printed at his own expense.) A more elaborated version of the proof would be published in 1826.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Proving that the general quintic (and higher) equations were unsolvable by radicals did not completely settle the matter, because the Abel–Ruffini theorem does not provide necessary and sufficient conditions for saying precisely which quintic (and higher) equations are unsolvable by radicals.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Abel was working on a complete characterization when he died in 1829.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] Prior to this publication, Liouville announced Galois' result to the academy in a speech he gave on 4 July 1843.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] A simplification of Abel's proof was published by Pierre Wantzel in 1845.
[src:galois-theory/abel-ruffini-theorem] In 1963, Vladimir Arnold discovered a topological proof of the Abel–Ruffini theorem, which served as a starting point for topological Galois theory.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] In mathematics, the **fundamental theorem of Galois theory** is a result that describes the structure of certain types of field extensions in relation to groups.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] It was proved by Évariste Galois in his development of Galois theory.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] In its most basic form, the theorem asserts that given a field extension $E/F$ that is finite and Galois, there is a one-to-one correspondence between its intermediate fields and subgroups of its Galois group.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] For finite extensions, the correspondence can be described explicitly as follows.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] The fundamental theorem says that this correspondence is a one-to-one correspondence if (and only if) $E/F$ is a Galois extension.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] For example, the topmost field E corresponds to the trivial subgroup of ${\text{Gal}}(E/F)$ , and the base field F corresponds to the whole group ${\text{Gal}}(E/F)$ .
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] The notation ${\text{Gal}}(E/F)$ is only used for Galois extensions.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] If $E/F$ is not Galois, then the "correspondence" gives only an injective (but not surjective) map from $\{{\text{subgroups of Aut}}(E/F)\}$ to $\{{\text{subfields of }}E/F\}$ , and a surjective (but not injective) map in the reverse direction.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] In particular, if $E/F$ is not Galois, then F is not the fixed field of any subgroup of ${\text{Aut}}(E/F)$ .
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] The correspondence has the following useful properties.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Its Galois group $G={\text{Gal}}(K/\mathbb {Q} )$ comprises the automorphisms of *K* which fix *a*.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Such automorphisms must send √2 to √2 or –√2, and send √3 to √3 or –√3, since they permute the roots of any irreducible polynomial.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] These are clearly automorphisms of *K*, respecting its addition and multiplication.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] which is isomorphic to the Klein four-group.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Its five subgroups correspond to the fields intermediate between the base $\mathbb {Q}$ and the extension *K*.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] The following is the simplest case where the Galois group is not abelian.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Consider the splitting field *K* of the irreducible polynomial $x^{3}-2$ over $\mathbb {Q}$ ; that is, $K=\mathbb {Q} (\theta ,\omega )$ where *θ* is a cube root of 2, and *ω* is a cube root of 1 (but not 1 itself).
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Since there are only 3! = 6 such permutations, *G* must be isomorphic to the symmetric group of all permutations of three objects.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Also, *g* can be considered as the complex conjugation mapping.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] here we denote an automorphism $\phi :E\to E$ by its value $\phi (\lambda )$ , so that $f(\lambda )\mapsto f(\phi (\lambda ))$ .
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] This group is isomorphic to $S_{3}$ (see: six cross-ratios).
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Let F be the fixed field of G , so that ${\rm {Gal}}(E/F)=G$ .
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] The Galois correspondence implies that every subfield of $E/F$ can be constructed this way.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Similar examples can be constructed for each of the symmetry groups of the platonic solids as these also have faithful actions on the projective line $\mathbb {P} ^{1}(\mathbb {C} )$ and hence on $\mathbb {C} (x)$ .
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Here we give an example of a finite extension $E/F$ which is not Galois, and with this we show that (the fundamental theorem of) Galois theory no longer works when $E/F$ is not Galois.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Then $E/F$ is a finite extension, but not a splitting field over F (since the minimal polynomials of ${\sqrt[{3}]{2}}$ has two complex roots that do not lie in E ).
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Now, G has only one subgroup, i.e., itself.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] The only intermediate field that contains $F=\mathbb {Q}$ is $E=\mathbb {Q} ({\sqrt[{3}]{2}})$ .
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] It follows that the Galois correspondence fails.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] The theorem classifies the intermediate fields of *E*/*F* in terms of group theory.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] This translation between intermediate fields and subgroups is key to showing that the general quintic equation is not solvable by radicals (see Abel–Ruffini theorem).
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] One first determines the Galois groups of radical extensions (extensions of the form *F*(α) where α is an *n*-th root of some element of *F*), and then uses the fundamental theorem to show that solvable extensions correspond to solvable groups.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Theories such as Kummer theory and class field theory are predicated on the fundamental theorem.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Given an infinite algebraic extension we can still define it to be Galois if it is normal and separable.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] The problem that one encounters in the infinite case is that the bijection in the fundamental theorem does not hold as we get too many subgroups generally.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] More precisely if we just take every subgroup we can in general find two different subgroups that fix the same intermediate field.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Therefore, we amend this by introducing a topology on the Galois group.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Let $E/F$ be a Galois extension (possibly infinite) and let $G={\text{Gal}}(E/F)$ be the Galois group of the extension.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Let ${\text{Int}}_{\text{F}}(E/F)=\{G_{i}={\text{Gal}}(L_{i}/F)~|~L_{i}/F{\text{ is a finite Galois extension and }}L_{i}\subseteq E\}$ be the set of the Galois groups of all finite intermediate Galois extensions.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Note that for all $i\in I$ we can define the maps $\varphi _{i}:G\rightarrow G_{i}$ by $\sigma \mapsto \sigma _{|L_{i}}$ .
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] We then define the *Krull topology* on G to be weakest topology such that for all $i\in I$ the maps $\varphi _{i}:G\rightarrow G_{i}$ are continuous, where we endow each $G_{i}$ with the discrete topology.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Stated differently $G\cong \varprojlim G_{i}$ as an inverse limit of topological groups (where again each $G_{i}$ is endowed with the discrete topology).
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] This makes G a profinite group (in fact every profinite group can be realised as the Galois group of a Galois extension, see for example ).
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Note that when $E/F$ is finite, the Krull topology is the discrete topology.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Now that we have defined a topology on the Galois group we can restate the fundamental theorem for infinite Galois extensions.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] Let ${\mathcal {F}}(E/F)$ denote the set of all intermediate field extensions of $E/F$ and let ${\mathcal {C}}(G)$ denote the set of all closed subgroups of $G={\text{Gal}}(E/F)$ endowed with the Krull topology.
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] One important thing one needs to check is that $\Phi$ is a well-defined map, that is that $\Phi (L)$ is a closed subgroup of G for all intermediate fields L .
[src:galois-theory/fundamental-theorem-of-galois-theory] This is proved in Ribes–Zalesskii, Theorem 2.11.3.
[src:galois-theory/galois-extension] In mathematics, a **Galois extension** is an algebraic field extension *E*/*F* that is normal and separable; or equivalently, *E*/*F* is algebraic, and the field fixed by the automorphism group Aut(*E*/*F*) is precisely the base field *F*.
[src:galois-theory/galois-extension] The significance of being a Galois extension is that the extension has a Galois group and obeys the fundamental theorem of Galois theory.
[src:galois-theory/galois-extension] A result of Emil Artin allows one to construct Galois extensions as follows: If *E* is a given field, and *G* is a finite group of automorphisms of *E* with fixed field *F*, then *E*/*F* is a Galois extension.
[src:galois-theory/galois-extension] The property of an extension being Galois behaves well with respect to field composition and intersection.
[src:galois-theory/galois-extension] There are two basic ways to construct examples of Galois extensions.
[src:galois-theory/galois-extension] Adjoining to the rational number field the square root of 2 gives a Galois extension, while adjoining the cubic root of 2 gives a non-Galois extension.
[src:galois-theory/galois-extension] Both these extensions are separable, because they have characteristic zero.
[src:galois-theory/galois-extension] The first of them is the splitting field of $x^{2}-2$ ; the second has normal closure that includes the complex cubic roots of unity, and so is not a splitting field.
[src:galois-theory/galois-extension] In fact, it has no automorphism other than the identity, because it is contained in the real numbers and $x^{3}-2$ has just one real root.
[src:galois-theory/galois-extension] For more detailed examples, see the page on the fundamental theorem of Galois theory.
[src:galois-theory/galois-extension] An algebraic closure ${\bar {K}}$ of an arbitrary field K is Galois over K if and only if K is a perfect field.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] In Galois theory, a branch of abstract algebra, the **Galois group** of a certain type of field extension is a symmetry group characterizing how it extends the base field.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] Each element of the Galois group is a transformation of the field extension which leaves each element of the base field fixed.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] This connection between fields and groups, given by the fundamental theorem of Galois theory, allows for group-theoretic tools to be used on problems in field theory, such as describing the solutions to quintic polynomials.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] The study of field extensions and their relationship to the polynomials that give rise to them via Galois groups is called Galois theory, so named in honor of Évariste Galois who first discovered them.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] A field is a set, like the rational numbers $\mathbb {Q}$ or the real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ , on which the four operations of addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division are defined and have certain standardized properties.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] Fields can be extended into larger fields with the same operations, such as how $\mathbb {Q}$ can be extended to $\mathbb {R}$ and $\mathbb {R}$ can be extended to the complex numbers $\mathbb {C}$ .
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] These extensions may arise when there is no solution to a given equation within the smaller field (the base field) but there is in the extension: for instance, $\mathbb {x^{2}=2}$ has no solution in $\mathbb {Q}$ but has two solutions in its extension $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] The problem of identifying and classifying the extensions of a field can be made easier by using group theory.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] Each extension of a field adds additional structure that is "invisible" to the base field, and the Galois group describes that structure.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] It does this by considering transformations which change the extension but leave the base field unchanged.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] For instance, the transformation of complex conjugation, which maps $a+bi\mapsto a-bi$ , leaves every real number fixed but generally does not leave complex numbers fixed.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] The "Galois group of $\mathbb {C}$ over $\mathbb {R}$ ", written ${\text{Gal}}(\mathbb {C} /\mathbb {R} )$ , is the cyclic group of order 2 (equivalently, the integers modulo 2), with its one non-identity element representing this transformation of complex conjugation.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] Suppose that E is an extension of the field F (written as $E/F$ and read "*E* over *F*").
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] An automorphism of $E/F$ is defined to be an automorphism of E that fixes F pointwise.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] In other words, an automorphism of $E/F$ is an isomorphism $\alpha :E\to E$ such that $\alpha (x)=x$ for each $x\in F$ .
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] The set of all automorphisms of $E/F$ forms a group with the operation of function composition.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] If $E/F$ is a Galois extension, then $\operatorname {Aut} (E/F)$ is called the **Galois group** of $E/F$ , and is usually denoted by $\operatorname {Gal} (E/F)$ .
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] If $E/F$ is not a Galois extension, then the Galois group of $E/F$ is sometimes defined as $\operatorname {Aut} (K/F)$ , where K is the Galois closure of E .
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] Another definition of the Galois group comes from the Galois group of an irreducible polynomial $f\in F[x]$ .
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] over the field K , then the **Galois group of the polynomial** f is defined as the Galois group of $K/F$ where K is minimal among all such fields.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] One of the important structure theorems from Galois theory comes from the fundamental theorem of Galois theory.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] Moreover, if H is a normal subgroup then $G/H\cong \operatorname {Gal} (E/k)$ .
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] And conversely, if $E/k$ is a normal field extension, then the associated subgroup in $\operatorname {Gal} (K/k)$ is a normal group.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] As a corollary, this can be inducted finitely many times.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] In the following examples F is a field, and $\mathbb {C} ,\mathbb {R} ,\mathbb {Q}$ are the fields of complex, real, and rational numbers, respectively.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] The notation *F*(*a*) indicates the field extension obtained by adjoining an element *a* to the field *F*.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] One of the basic propositions required for completely determining the Galois group of a finite field extension is the following: Given a polynomial $f(x)\in F[x]$ , let $E/F$ be its splitting field extension.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] A useful tool for determining the Galois group of a polynomial comes from Eisenstein's criterion.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] $\operatorname {Gal} (F/F)$ is the trivial group that has a single element, namely the identity automorphism.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] Another example of a Galois group which is trivial is $\operatorname {Aut} (\mathbb {R} /\mathbb {Q} ).$ Indeed, it can be shown that any automorphism of $\mathbb {R}$ must preserve the ordering of the real numbers and hence must be the identity.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] Consider the field $K=\mathbb {Q} ({\sqrt[{3}]{2}}).$ The group $\operatorname {Aut} (K/\mathbb {Q} )$ contains only the identity automorphism.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] are missing from the extension—in other words *K* is not a splitting field.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] The Galois group $\operatorname {Gal} (\mathbb {C} /\mathbb {R} )$ has two elements, the identity automorphism and the complex conjugation automorphism.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] The degree two field extension $\mathbb {Q} ({\sqrt {2}})/\mathbb {Q}$ has the Galois group $\operatorname {Gal} (\mathbb {Q} ({\sqrt {2}})/\mathbb {Q} )$ with two elements, the identity automorphism and the automorphism $\sigma$ which exchanges ${\sqrt {2}}$ and $-{\sqrt {2}}$ .
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] Another useful class of examples comes from the splitting fields of cyclotomic polynomials.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] whose degree is $\phi (n)$ , Euler's totient function at n .
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] Then, the splitting field over $\mathbb {Q}$ is $\mathbb {Q} (\zeta _{n})$ and has automorphisms $\sigma _{a}$ sending $\zeta _{n}\mapsto \zeta _{n}^{a}$ for $1\leq a<n$ relatively prime to n .
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] Since the degree of the field is equal to the degree of the polynomial, these automorphisms generate the Galois group.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] In fact, any finite abelian group can be found as the Galois group of some subfield of a cyclotomic field extension by the Kronecker–Weber theorem.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] Another useful class of examples of Galois groups with finite abelian groups comes from finite fields.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] If *q* is a prime power, and if $F=\mathbb {F} _{q}$ and $E=\mathbb {F} _{q^{n}}$ denote the Galois fields of order q and $q^{n}$ respectively, then $\operatorname {Gal} (E/F)$ is cyclic of order *n* and generated by the Frobenius homomorphism.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] The field extension $\mathbb {Q} {\bigl (}{\sqrt {2}},{\sqrt {3}}~\!{\bigr )}{\big /}\mathbb {Q}$ is an example of a degree 4 field extension.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] This has two automorphisms $\sigma ,\tau$ where $\sigma {\bigl (}{\sqrt {2}}~\!{\bigr )}=-{\sqrt {2}}$ and $\tau {\bigl (}{\sqrt {3}}~\!{\bigr )}=-{\sqrt {3}}.$ Since these two generators define a group of order 4 , the Klein four-group, they determine the entire Galois group.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] Since $\sigma _{2}$ generates this group, the Galois group is isomorphic to $\mathbb {Z} /4\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] Consider now $L=\mathbb {Q} ({\sqrt[{3}]{2}},\omega ),$ where $\omega$ is a primitive cube root of unity.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] The Quaternion group can be found as the Galois group of a field extension of $\mathbb {Q}$ .
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] For example, $f(x)=x^{5}-4x+2\in \mathbb {Q} [x]$ is irreducible from Eisenstein's criterion.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] Plotting the graph of f with graphing software or paper shows it has three real roots, hence two complex roots, showing its Galois group is $S_{5}$ .
