[src:galois-theory/galois-group] Since we have taken the hypothesis that w lies over v (i.e. there is a Galois field extension $K_{w}/k_{v}$ ), the field morphism $s_{w}$ is in fact an isomorphism of $k_{v}$ -algebras.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] then there is a surjection of the global Galois group to the local Galois group such that there is an isomorphism between the local Galois group and the isotropy subgroup.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] where the vertical arrows are isomorphisms.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] This gives a technique for constructing Galois groups of local fields using global Galois groups.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] A basic example of a field extension with an infinite group of automorphisms is $\operatorname {Aut} (\mathbb {C} /\mathbb {Q} )$ , since it contains every algebraic field extension $E/\mathbb {Q}$ .
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] One of the most studied classes of infinite Galois group is the absolute Galois group, which is an infinite, profinite group defined as the inverse limit of all finite Galois extensions $E/F$ for a fixed field.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] where ${\overline {F}}$ is the separable closure of the field F .
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] Another readily computable example comes from the field extension $\mathbb {Q} ({\sqrt {2}},{\sqrt {3}},{\sqrt {5}},\ldots )/\mathbb {Q}$ containing the square root of every positive prime.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] and using the computation of the Galois groups.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] The significance of an extension being Galois is that it obeys the fundamental theorem of Galois theory: the closed (with respect to the Krull topology) subgroups of the Galois group correspond to the intermediate fields of the field extension.
[src:galois-theory/galois-group] If $E/F$ is a Galois extension, then $\operatorname {Gal} (E/F)$ can be given a topology, called the Krull topology, that makes it into a profinite group.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] In mathematics, **Galois theory**, originally introduced by Évariste Galois, provides a connection between field theory and group theory.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] This connection, the fundamental theorem of Galois theory, allows reducing certain problems in field theory to group theory, which makes them simpler and easier to understand.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Galois introduced the subject for studying roots of polynomials.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] This widely generalizes the Abel–Ruffini theorem, which asserts that a general polynomial of degree at least five cannot be solved by radicals.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Galois' work was published by Joseph Liouville fourteen years after his death.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] The theory took longer to become popular among mathematicians and to be well understood.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Galois theory has been generalized to Galois connections and Grothendieck's Galois theory.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] The Abel–Ruffini theorem provides a counterexample proving that there are polynomial equations for which such a formula cannot exist.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Galois' theory provides a much more complete answer to this question, by explaining why it *is* possible to solve some equations, including all those of degree four or lower, in the above manner, and why it is not possible for most equations of degree five or higher.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Furthermore, it provides a means of determining whether a particular equation can be solved that is both conceptually clear and easily expressed as an algorithm.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Galois' theory also gives a clear insight into questions concerning problems in compass and straightedge construction.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] It gives an elegant characterization of the ratios of lengths that can be constructed with this method.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Why is it not possible to trisect every angle using a compass and a straightedge?
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Why is doubling the cube not possible with the same method?
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Galois' theory originated in the study of symmetric functions – the coefficients of a monic polynomial are (up to sign) the elementary symmetric polynomials in the roots.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] This was first formalized by the 16th-century French mathematician François Viète, in Viète's formulas, for the case of positive real roots.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] See Discriminant § Low degrees for details.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] The cubic was first partly solved by the 15–16th-century Italian mathematician Scipione del Ferro, who did not however publish his results; this method, though, only solved one type of cubic equation.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] This solution was then rediscovered independently in 1535 by Niccolò Fontana Tartaglia, who shared it with Gerolamo Cardano, asking him to not publish it.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Cardano then extended this to numerous other cases, using similar arguments; see more details at Cardano's method.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] With the benefit of modern notation and complex numbers, the formulae in this book do work in the general case, but Cardano did not know this.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] It was Rafael Bombelli who managed to understand how to work with complex numbers in order to solve all forms of cubic equation.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Crucially, however, he did not consider *composition* of permutations.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Lagrange's method did not extend to quintic equations or higher, because the resolvent had higher degree.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] The quintic was almost proven to have no general solutions by radicals by Paolo Ruffini in 1799, whose key insight was to use permutation *groups*, not just a single permutation.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] His solution contained a gap, which Cauchy considered minor, though this was not patched until the work of the Norwegian mathematician Niels Henrik Abel, who published a proof in 1824, thus establishing the Abel–Ruffini theorem.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] This group was always solvable for polynomials of degree four or less, but not always so for polynomials of degree five and greater, which explains why there is no general solution in higher degrees.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] In 1830 Galois (at the age of 18) submitted to the French Academy of Sciences a memoir on his theory of solvability by radicals; Galois' paper was ultimately rejected in 1831 as being too sketchy and for giving a condition in terms of the roots of the equation instead of its coefficients.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Galois then died in a duel in 1832, and his paper, "*Mémoire sur les conditions de résolubilité des équations par radicaux*", remained unpublished until 1846 when it was published by Joseph Liouville accompanied by some of his own explanations.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Prior to this publication, Liouville announced Galois' result to the Academy of Sciences in a speech he gave on 4 July 1843.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Galois' theory was notoriously difficult for his contemporaries to understand, especially to the level where they could expand on it.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] For example, in his 1846 commentary, Liouville completely missed the group-theoretic core of Galois' method.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Joseph Alfred Serret who attended some of Liouville's talks, included Galois' theory in his 1866 (third edition) of his textbook *Cours d'algèbre supérieure*.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Serret's pupil, Camille Jordan, had an even better understanding reflected in his 1870 book *Traité des substitutions et des équations algébriques*.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Outside France, Galois' theory remained more obscure for a longer period.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] In Britain, Cayley failed to grasp its depth and popular British algebra textbooks did not even mention Galois' theory until well after the turn of the century.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] In Germany, Kronecker's writings focused more on Abel's result.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Dedekind wrote little about Galois' theory, but lectured on it at Göttingen in 1858, showing a very good understanding.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Eugen Netto's books of the 1880s, based on Jordan's *Traité*, made Galois theory accessible to a wider German and American audience as did Heinrich Martin Weber's 1895 algebra textbook.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Given a polynomial, it may be that some of the roots are connected by various algebraic equations.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] For example, it may be that for two of the roots, say *A* and *B*, that *A*2 + 5*B*3 = 7.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] The central idea of Galois' theory is to consider permutations (or rearrangements) of the roots such that *any* algebraic equation satisfied by the roots is *still satisfied* after the roots have been permuted.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Originally, the theory had been developed for algebraic equations whose coefficients are rational numbers.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] It extends naturally to equations with coefficients in any field, but this will not be considered in the simple examples below.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] These permutations together form a permutation group, also called the Galois group of the polynomial, which is explicitly described in the following examples.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] If we exchange *A* and *B* in either of the last two equations we obtain another true statement.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] For example, the equation *A* + *B* = 4 becomes *B* + *A* = 4.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] It is more generally true that this holds for *every* possible algebraic relation between *A* and *B* such that all coefficients are rational; that is, in any such relation, swapping *A* and *B* yields another true relation.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] This results from the theory of symmetric polynomials, which, in this case, may be replaced by formula manipulations involving the binomial theorem.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] One might object that *A* and *B* are related by the algebraic equation *A* − *B* − 2√3 = 0, which does not remain true when *A* and *B* are exchanged.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] However, this relation is not considered here, because it has the coefficient −2√3 which is not rational.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] We conclude that the Galois group of the polynomial *x*2 − 4*x* + 1 consists of two permutations: the identity permutation which leaves *A* and *B* untouched, and the transposition permutation which exchanges *A* and *B*.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] As all groups with two elements are isomorphic, this Galois group is isomorphic to the multiplicative group {1, −1}.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] A similar discussion applies to any quadratic polynomial *ax*2 + *bx* + *c*, where *a*, *b* and *c* are rational numbers.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Among the 24 possible permutations of these four roots, four are particularly simple, those consisting in the sign change of 0, 1, or 2 square roots.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] They form a group that is isomorphic to the Klein four-group.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Galois theory implies that, since the polynomial is irreducible, the Galois group has at least four elements.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] For proving that the Galois group consists of these four permutations, it suffices thus to show that every element of the Galois group is determined by the image of A, which can be shown as follows.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] The members of the Galois group must preserve any algebraic equation with rational coefficients involving *A*, *B*, *C* and *D*.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] This implies that the Galois group is isomorphic to the Klein four-group.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] In the modern approach, one starts with a field extension *L*/*K* (read "*L* over *K*"), and examines the group of automorphisms of *L* that fix *K*.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] See the article on Galois groups for further explanation and examples.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] The connection between the two approaches is as follows.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] The coefficients of the polynomial in question should be chosen from the base field *K*.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] The top field *L* should be the field obtained by adjoining the roots of the polynomial in question to the base field *K*.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Any permutation of the roots which respects algebraic equations as described above gives rise to an automorphism of *L*/*K*, and vice versa.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] In the first example above, we were studying the extension **Q**(√3)/**Q**, where **Q** is the field of rational numbers, and **Q**(√3) is the field obtained from **Q** by adjoining √3.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] There are several advantages to the modern approach over the permutation group approach.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] The notion of a solvable group in group theory allows one to determine whether a polynomial is solvable in radicals, depending on whether its Galois group has the property of solvability.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] In essence, each field extension *L*/*K* corresponds to a factor group in a composition series of the Galois group.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] If all the factor groups in its composition series are cyclic, the Galois group is called *solvable*, and all of the elements of the corresponding field can be found by repeatedly taking roots, products, and sums of elements from the base field (usually **Q**).
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] The Abel–Ruffini theorem results from the fact that for *n* > 4 the symmetric group *S**n* contains a simple, noncyclic, normal subgroup, namely the alternating group *A**n*.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Van der Waerden cites the polynomial *f*(*x*) = *x*5 − *x* − 1.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] By the rational root theorem, this has no rational zeroes.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Neither does it have linear factors modulo 2 or 3.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] The Galois group of *f*(*x*) modulo 2 is cyclic of order 6, because *f*(*x*) modulo 2 factors into polynomials of orders 2 and 3, (*x*2 + *x* + 1)(*x*3 + *x*2 + 1).
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] It is known that a Galois group modulo a prime is isomorphic to a subgroup of the Galois group over the rationals.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] A permutation group on 5 objects with elements of orders 6 and 5 must be the symmetric group *S*5, which is therefore the Galois group of *f*(*x*).
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] This is one of the simplest examples of a non-solvable quintic polynomial.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] According to Serge Lang, Emil Artin was fond of this example.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] The *inverse Galois problem* is to find a field extension with a given Galois group.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] As long as one does not also specify the ground field, the problem is not very difficult, and all finite groups do occur as Galois groups.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] For showing this, one may proceed as follows.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Choose a field *K* and a finite group *G*.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Cayley's theorem says that *G* is (up to isomorphism) a subgroup of the symmetric group *S* on the elements of *G*.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Choose indeterminates {*x**α*}, one for each element *α* of *G*, and adjoin them to *K* to get the field *F* = *K*({*x**α*}).
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Contained within *F* is the field *L* of symmetric rational functions in the {*x**α*}.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] The Galois group of *F*/*L* is *S*, by a basic result of Emil Artin.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] *G* acts on *F* by restriction of action of *S*.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] If the fixed field of this action is *M*, then, by the fundamental theorem of Galois theory, the Galois group of *F*/*M* is *G*.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] On the other hand, it is an open problem whether every finite group is the Galois group of a field extension of the field **Q** of the rational numbers.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Igor Shafarevich proved that every solvable finite group is the Galois group of some extension of **Q**.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Various people have solved the inverse Galois problem for selected non-Abelian simple groups.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Existence of solutions has been shown for all but possibly one (Mathieu group *M*23) of the 26 sporadic simple groups.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] There is even a polynomial with integral coefficients whose Galois group is the Monster group.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] In the form mentioned above, including in particular the fundamental theorem of Galois theory, the theory only considers Galois extensions, which are in particular separable.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] General field extensions can be split into a separable, followed by a purely inseparable field extension.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] For a purely inseparable extension *F* / *K*, there is a Galois theory where the Galois group is replaced by the vector space of derivations, $Der_{K}(F,F)$ , i.e., *K*-linear endomorphisms of *F* satisfying the Leibniz rule.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] In this correspondence, an intermediate field *E* is assigned $Der_{E}(F,F)\subset Der_{K}(F,F)$ .
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Conversely, a subspace $V\subset Der_{K}(F,F)$ satisfying appropriate further conditions is mapped to $\{x\in F,f(x)=0\ \forall f\in V\}$ .
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] Under the assumption $F^{p}\subset K$ , Jacobson (1944) showed that this establishes a one-to-one correspondence.
[src:galois-theory/galois-theory] The condition imposed by Jacobson has been removed by Brantner & Waldron (2020), by giving a correspondence using notions of derived algebraic geometry.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] There is also a more general definition that applies when E is not necessarily algebraic over F.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] An extension that is not separable is said to be *inseparable*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] Every algebraic extension of a field of characteristic zero is separable, and every algebraic extension of a finite field is separable.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] It follows that most extensions that are considered in mathematics are separable.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] Nevertheless, the concept of separability is important, as the existence of inseparable extensions is the main obstacle for extending many theorems proved in characteristic zero to non-zero characteristic.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] For example, the fundamental theorem of Galois theory is a theorem about normal extensions, which remains true in non-zero characteristic only if the extensions are also assumed to be separable.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] The opposite concept, a purely inseparable extension, also occurs naturally, as every algebraic extension may be decomposed uniquely as a purely inseparable extension of a separable extension.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] The simplest nontrivial example of a (purely) inseparable extension is $E=\mathbb {F} _{p}(x)\supseteq F=\mathbb {F} _{p}(x^{p})$ , fields of rational functions in the indeterminate *x* with coefficients in the finite field $\mathbb {F} _{p}=\mathbb {Z} /(p)$ .
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] This is a simple algebraic extension of degree *p*, as $E=F[x]$ , but it is not a normal extension since the Galois group ${\text{Gal}}(E/F)$ is trivial.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] An arbitrary polynomial *f* with coefficients in some field *F* is said to have *distinct roots* or to be square-free if it has deg *f* roots in some extension field $E\supseteq F$ .
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] For instance, the polynomial *g*(*X*) = *X* 2 − 1 has precisely deg *g* = 2 roots in the complex plane; namely 1 and −1, and hence *does have* distinct roots.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] On the other hand, the polynomial *h*(*X*) = (*X* − 2)2, which is the square of a non-constant polynomial *does not* have distinct roots, as its degree is two, and 2 is its only root.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] Every polynomial may be factored in linear factors over an algebraic closure of the field of its coefficients.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] Therefore, the polynomial does not have distinct roots if and only if it is divisible by the square of a polynomial of positive degree.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] This is the case if and only if the greatest common divisor of the polynomial and its derivative is not a constant.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] Thus for testing if a polynomial is square-free, it is not necessary to consider explicitly any field extension nor to compute the roots.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] In this context, the case of irreducible polynomials requires some care.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] A priori, it may seem that being divisible by a square is impossible for an irreducible polynomial, which has no non-constant divisor except itself.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] However, irreducibility depends on the ambient field, and a polynomial may be irreducible over *F* and reducible over some extension of *F*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] Similarly, divisibility by a square depends on the ambient field.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] If an irreducible polynomial *f* over *F* is divisible by a square over some field extension, then (by the discussion above) the greatest common divisor of *f* and its derivative *f*′ is not constant.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] Note that the coefficients of *f*′ belong to the same field as those of *f*, and the greatest common divisor of two polynomials is independent of the ambient field, so the greatest common divisor of *f* and *f*′ has coefficients in *F*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] Since *f* is irreducible in *F*, this greatest common divisor is necessarily *f* itself.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] A polynomial such as this one, whose formal derivative is zero, is said to be *inseparable*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] Polynomials that are not inseparable are said to be *separable*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] A *separable extension* is an extension that may be generated by *separable elements*, that is elements whose minimal polynomials are separable.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] An irreducible polynomial *f* in *F*[*X*] is separable if and only if it has distinct roots in any extension of *F*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] That is, if it is the product of distinct linear factors *X* - *a* in some algebraic closure of *F*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] Let *f* in *F*[*X*] be an irreducible polynomial and *f* ' its formal derivative.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] Since the formal derivative of a positive degree polynomial can be zero only if the field has prime characteristic, for an irreducible polynomial to not be separable, its coefficients must lie in a field of prime characteristic.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] More generally, an irreducible (non-zero) polynomial *f* in *F*[*X*] is not separable, if and only if the characteristic of *F* is a (non-zero) prime number *p*, and *f*(*X*)=*g*(*X**p*) for some *irreducible* polynomial *g* in *F*[*X*].
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] By repeated application of this property, it follows that in fact, $f(X)=g(X^{p^{n}})$ for a non-negative integer *n* and some *separable irreducible* polynomial *g* in *F*[*X*] (where *F* is assumed to have prime characteristic *p*).
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] If the Frobenius endomorphism $x\mapsto x^{p}$ of *F* is not surjective, there is an element $a\in F$ that is not a *p*th power of an element of *F*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] In this case, the polynomial $X^{p}-a$ is irreducible and inseparable.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] If *K* is a finite field of prime characteristic *p*, and if *X* is an indeterminate, then the field of rational functions over *K*, *K*(*X*), is necessarily imperfect, and the polynomial *f*(*Y*)=*Y**p*−*X* is inseparable (its formal derivative in *Y* is 0).
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] More generally, if *F* is any field of (non-zero) prime characteristic for which the Frobenius endomorphism is not an automorphism, *F* possesses an inseparable algebraic extension.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] A field *F* is perfect if and only if all irreducible polynomials are separable.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] It follows that *F* is perfect if and only if either *F* has characteristic zero, or *F* has (non-zero) prime characteristic *p* and the Frobenius endomorphism of *F* is an automorphism.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] Let $E\supseteq F$ be a field extension.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] An element $\alpha \in E$ is **separable** over *F* if it is algebraic over *F*, and its minimal polynomial is separable (the minimal polynomial of an element is necessarily irreducible).
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] If $\alpha ,\beta \in E$ are separable over *F*, then $\alpha +\beta$ , $\alpha \beta$ and $1/\alpha$ are separable over *F*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] Thus the set of all elements in *E* separable over *F* forms a subfield of *E*, called the **separable closure** of *F* in *E*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] The separable closure of *F* in an algebraic closure of *F* is simply called the **separable closure** of *F*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] Like the algebraic closure, it is unique up to an isomorphism, and in general, this isomorphism is not unique.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] A field extension $E\supseteq F$ is **separable**, if *E* is the separable closure of *F* in *E*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] This is the case if and only if *E* is generated over *F* by separable elements.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] If $E\supseteq L\supseteq F$ are field extensions, then *E* is separable over *F* if and only if *E* is separable over *L* and *L* is separable over *F*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] If $E\supseteq F$ is a finite extension (that is *E* is a *F*-vector space of finite dimension), then the following are equivalent.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] 3. $E=F(a)$ where *a* is a separable element of *E*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] If *K* is an algebraic closure of *F*, then there are exactly $[E:F]$ field homomorphisms of *E* into *K* that fix *F*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] For any normal extension *K* of *F* that contains *E*, then there are exactly $[E:F]$ field homomorphisms of *E* into *K* that fix *F*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] The equivalence of 3. and 1. is known as the primitive element theorem or Artin's theorem on primitive elements.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] Properties 4. and 5. are the basis of Galois theory, and, in particular, of the fundamental theorem of Galois theory.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] Let $E\supseteq F$ be an algebraic extension of fields of characteristic *p*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] The separable closure of *F* in *E* is $S=\{\alpha \in E\mid \alpha {\text{ is separable over }}F\}.$ For every element $x\in E\setminus S$ there exists a positive integer *k* such that $x^{p^{k}}\in S,$ and thus *E* is a purely inseparable extension of *S*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] It follows that *S* is the unique intermediate field that is *separable* over *F* and over which *E* is *purely inseparable*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] If $E\supseteq F$ is a finite extension, its degree [*E* : *F*] is the product of the degrees [*S* : *F*] and [*E* : *S*].
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] The former, often denoted [*E* : *F*]sep, is referred to as the *separable part* of [*E* : *F*], or as the **separable degree** of *E*/*F*; the latter is referred to as the *inseparable part* of the degree or the **inseparable degree**.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] The inseparable degree is 1 in characteristic zero and a power of *p* in characteristic *p* > 0.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] On the other hand, an arbitrary algebraic extension $E\supseteq F$ may not possess an intermediate extension *K* that is *purely inseparable* over *F* and over which *E* is *separable*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] However, such an intermediate extension may exist if, for example, $E\supseteq F$ is a finite degree normal extension (in this case, *K* is the fixed field of the Galois group of *E* over *F*).
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] Suppose that such an intermediate extension does exist, and [*E* : *F*] is finite, then [*S* : *F*] = [*E* : *K*], where *S* is the separable closure of *F* in *E*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] The known proofs of this equality use the fact that if $K\supseteq F$ is a purely inseparable extension, and if *f* is a separable irreducible polynomial in *F*[*X*], then *f* remains irreducible in *K*[*X*]).
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] This equality implies that, if [*E* : *F*] is finite, and *U* is an intermediate field between *F* and *E*, then [*E* : *F*]sep = [*E* : *U*]sep⋅[*U* : *F*]sep.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] The separable closure *F*sep of a field *F* is the separable closure of *F* in an algebraic closure of *F*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] It is the maximal Galois extension of *F*.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] By definition, *F* is perfect if and only if its separable and algebraic closures coincide.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] Separability problems may arise when dealing with transcendental extensions.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] This is typically the case for algebraic geometry over a field of prime characteristic, where the function field of an algebraic variety has a transcendence degree over the ground field that is equal to the dimension of the variety.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] For defining the separability of a transcendental extension, it is natural to use the fact that every field extension is an algebraic extension of a purely transcendental extension.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] A *separating transcendence basis* of an extension $E\supseteq F$ is a transcendence basis *T* of *E* such that *E* is a separable algebraic extension of *F*(*T*).
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] A finitely generated field extension is *separable* if and only it has a separating transcendence basis; an extension that is not finitely generated is called separable if every finitely generated subextension has a separating transcendence basis.
[src:galois-theory/separable-extension] Let $E\supseteq F$ be a field extension of characteristic exponent *p* (that is *p* = 1 in characteristic zero and, otherwise, *p* is the characteristic).
