[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] In mathematics, more specifically in the field of group theory, a **solvable group** or **soluble group** is a group that can be constructed from abelian groups using extensions.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] Equivalently, a solvable group is a group whose derived series terminates in the trivial subgroup.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] Historically, the word "solvable" arose from Galois theory and the proof of the general unsolvability of quintic equations.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] Specifically, a polynomial equation is solvable in radicals if and only if the corresponding Galois group is solvable (note this theorem holds only in characteristic 0).
