[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] Each of the defining group actions (for example, $fgh^{3}j^{4}$ ) changes a single extension while keeping all of the other extensions fixed.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] It is isomorphic to $(\mathbb {Z} _{5}\rtimes _{\varphi }\mathbb {Z} _{4})\times (\mathbb {Z} _{2}\times \mathbb {Z} _{2})$ , where $\varphi _{h}(j)=hjh^{-1}=j^{2}$ , defined using the semidirect product and direct product of the cyclic groups. $\mathbb {Z} _{4}$ is not a normal subgroup.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] where every subgroup is the commutator subgroup of the previous one, eventually reaches the trivial subgroup of *G*.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] These two definitions are equivalent, since for every group *H* and every normal subgroup *N* of *H*, the quotient *H*/*N* is abelian if and only if *N* includes the commutator subgroup of *H*.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] The least *n* such that *G*(*n*) = 1 is called the **derived length** of the solvable group *G*.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] For finite groups, an equivalent definition is that a solvable group is a group with a composition series all of whose factors are cyclic groups of prime order.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] This is equivalent because a finite group has finite composition length, and every simple abelian group is cyclic of prime order.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] The Jordan–Hölder theorem guarantees that if one composition series has this property, then all composition series will have this property as well.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] For the Galois group of a polynomial, these cyclic groups correspond to *n*th roots (radicals) over some field.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] The basic example of solvable groups are abelian groups.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] They are trivially solvable since a subnormal series is formed by just the group itself and the trivial group.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] But non-abelian groups may or may not be solvable.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] More generally, all nilpotent groups are solvable.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] In particular, finite *p*-groups are solvable, as all finite *p*-groups are nilpotent.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] where the kernel $\mathbb {Z} /2$ is the subgroup generated by $-1$ .
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] Group extensions form the prototypical examples of solvable groups.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] In fact, all solvable groups can be formed from such group extensions.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] A small example of a solvable, non-nilpotent group is the symmetric group *S*3.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] In fact, as the smallest simple non-abelian group is *A*5, (the alternating group of degree 5) it follows that *every* group with order less than 60 is solvable.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] The Feit–Thompson theorem states that every finite group of odd order is solvable.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] In particular this implies that if a finite group is simple, it is either a prime cyclic or of even order.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] The group *S*5 is not solvable—it has a composition series {E, *A*5, *S*5} (and the Jordan–Hölder theorem states that every other composition series is equivalent to that one), giving factor groups isomorphic to *A*5 and *C*2; and *A*5 is not abelian.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] Generalizing this argument, coupled with the fact that *A**n* is a normal, maximal, non-abelian simple subgroup of *S**n* for *n* > 4, we see that *S**n* is not solvable for *n* > 4.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] This is a key step in the proof that for every *n* > 4 there are polynomials of degree *n* which are not solvable by radicals (Abel–Ruffini theorem).
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] This property is also used in complexity theory in the proof of Barrington's theorem.
