[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] For a linear algebraic group G , a Borel subgroup is defined as a subgroup which is closed, connected, and solvable in G , and is a maximal possible subgroup with these properties (note the first two are topological properties).
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] For example, in $GL_{n}$ and $SL_{n}$ the groups of upper-triangular, or lower-triangular matrices are two of the Borel subgroups.
[src:galois-theory/solvable-group] The example given above, the subgroup B in $GL_{2}$ , is a Borel subgroup.
